    id: "paeds-amedex-0012",
    topic: "Paediatrics",
    subtopic: "Pediatric hematuria evaluation",
    stem: `A 9-year-old girl was brought to your practice two weeks ago with a fever. Your assessment established an upper respiratory tract infection (URTI) as the diagnosis; however, you were also concerned about 3+ blood and 1+ proteinuria on a dipstick urine exam; therefore, you advised a follow-up in two weeks. Today, she is back for it, and dipstick urine shows 2+ blood and no proteinuria. You arrange for a formal urinalysis that returns negative for glomerular red blood cells and casts. Which one of the following is the most important next step in management?`,
