    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Based on current guidelines by the Royal Children's Hospital (RCH), asymptomatic isolated hematuria in a child with a febrile disease other than a urinary tract infection should be followed up once the febrile disease settles. This child has undergone another urine exam in two weeks, which still shows isolated hematuria of non-glomerular origin. For this child, a urine culture/sensitivity to exclude urinary tract infections is the most appropriate next step in management. DMSA scan (dimercaptosuccinic acid, bound to technetium 99m) isotype is circulated through the body. 95% of the radiopharmaceutical is bound to the renal cortex, and the remaining 5% is usually excreted into the urine. Modern gamma cameras capable of performing single-photon emission tomography (SPECT) can reconstruct 3-dimensional images of the kidneys. In children, the accepted indications for a DMSA scan include renal scars as a result of an insult (usually recurrent urinary tract infections) or reflux-associated nephropathy. Ultrasound is useful in diagnosing renal morphology and assessing renal damage, especially in hematuria, edema, and hypertension where underlying nephritis is suspected. IVP (Intravenous Pyelography) is used to check urine flow if there is concern regarding kidney, ureter, or bladder blockage or to check the function and appearance of the urinary tract after surgery to prevent blockages from causing permanent kidney damage. ASOT (Anti-streptolysin O Titer) is used in the case of post-streptococcal GN in a school-aged child with macroscopic hematuria, edema due to fluid retention, and possibly a headache due to hypertension.`,
