    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Hemorrhage after tonsillectomy is the most common complication of the procedure. The bleeding may occur in the early postoperative period or as delayed as 5 to 10 days. Late bleeding is usually secondary to infection of the tonsillar fossae. Typically, there is minor bleeding, but blood pouring develops afterwards; therefore, any bleeding, even trivial, must be considered serious in all cases. Post-tonsillectomy hemorrhage is a life-threatening condition that requires prompt management in all cases (even if only a little blood is spat out and bleeding stops again – all these cases should be dealt with caution – particularly the children). Management of post-tonsillectomy hemorrhage includes: Resuscitation – 2 large bore cannulas with blood; Reservation of cross-matched packed red cells; Intravenous antibiotics: with 1.2g Benzyl Penicillin, 6-hourly + 500mg of metronidazole, 12-hourly; Analgesia without NSAIDs (NSAIDs may increase the chance of bleeding); Hydrogen peroxide gargle - 20mls of hydrogen peroxide diluted with water in a ratio of 1:6. This gargle should be used every 4 hours; it should be used when a large clot overlies one of the tonsil beds. Of the given options, the only one in the management plan of this patient is the administration of intravenous antibiotics. (Option A) Packing the tonsils is neither practical nor effective. (Option B) Antibiotics in oral forms are not recommended for management. (Option D) Exploration might be indicated; however, most patients will respond to more conservative management. (Option E) The patient should be kept nil by mouth (NBM) because it is very likely that emergency surgery will become inevitable; therefore, giving him ice cream or cold fluids is an incorrect option.`,
