    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Intermittent abdominal pain in children is a frequent reason for seeking medical attention by concerned parents. The causes of intermittent abdominal pain are diverse, ranging from benign conditions such as functional abdominal pain to grave diseases such as childhood malignancies. As usual, a thorough history and physical examination are the cornerstones of the approach to such children. Associated symptoms can also help narrow down the differential diagnoses. Of the options, ureteropelvic junction (UPJ) obstruction is the only likely diagnosis justifying the clinical scenario. UPJ obstruction is by far the most common cause of pediatric hydronephrosis, occurring in 1 per 1000-2000 newborns. Widespread use of antenatal ultrasonography and the advent of modern imaging techniques have resulted in earlier and more common diagnoses of the condition. In older children, periodic abdominal pain with vomiting is a common symptom. These symptoms are probably caused by intermittent kinking of the UPJ. If obstruction does not resolve, severe hydronephrosis and pelvic distention can follow, presenting with flank pain or even tenderness. Although rarely seen in developed countries, massive dilation of the renal pelvis and kidney can fill the entire flank and abdomen. In younger adults, the typical presentation is episodic flank pain following diuresis. (Option A) Wilms tumour is the most common intra-abdominal malignant tumour of childhood. It often presents with a smooth, firm abdominal mass that usually does not cross the midline. Abdominal pain, either constant and vague or intermittent, is another finding. Hematuria and hypertension are other possible manifestations. Unlike the mass in the scenario, the abdominal mass found in Wilms's tumour is non-tender, making Wilms's tumour a less likely diagnosis. (Option B) Neuroblastoma is the most common extracranial malignant tumour in childhood. The initial presentation is most commonly within the first 2 years of life. The tumour is intraabdominal in two-thirds of cases. Of these cases, two-thirds originated from adrenal glands. It can also present with a palpable abdominal mass that is non-tender. However, the age of the child and the tenderness of the mass are against neuroblastoma as the diagnosis. (Options D and E) Based on physical findings or other clinical features, these are less likely diagnoses.`,
