    explanation: `The scenario represents premature isolated adrenarche (development of pubic hair before age 8 in girls or 9 in boys in the absence of other sexual characteristics like thelarche or menarche). This is a benign variant of normal development if weight and height are normal for age. No investigations are required for premature isolated adrenarche as FSH, LH, 17-hydroxyprogesterone, and testosterone are all normal. The only laboratory finding might be slight elevation of DHEAS. It is recommended that children with premature isolated adrenarche are followed every 3-6 months for surveillance of puberty development and linear progression and velocity of growth. Bone age assessment is considered in constitutional growth delay (CGD) alongside exclusion of other causes of delayed puberty/growth to confirm the diagnosis or where the child is small for age. This child has normal weight and height for age. Ultrasound of the pelvis is the study of choice for girls whose periods are overdue despite development of other secondary sexual characteristics, normal body measures, and absence of features suggesting chromosomal abnormalities such as Turner syndrome.`,
