    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `The clinical presentation and photograph suggest the thyroglossal duct cyst (TDC) as the most likely diagnosis. TDC is the most common type of developmental cyst encountered in the neck region. TDC occurs when the thyroglossal duct fails to obliterate and forms a bridge between the base of the tongue and the thyroid gland. A TDC usually presents with an asymptomatic palpable midline neck mass, usually at or below the level of the hyoid bone, above the thyroid cartilage. The mass is most often in the midline, although it can present slightly off the midline to one side or the other. A TDC may present in childhood (less than 50%) or later in life, usually as a young adult below the age of 20. On examination, a TDC moves up when the tongue is protruded and up and down upon swallowing, reflecting the attachment of these cysts to the base of the tongue by the thyroglossal tract. Some patients have neck or throat pain or dysphagia, but most are just concerned about the lump itself. A TDC may become complicated. Complications of TDCs include: Infection; Malignancy; Overgrowth and pressure of the underlying structures; Rupture and fistula formation. The most common complication is infection. An infected TDC usually presents with redness and swelling (see image below). Malignancy (option B) is the second most common complication of TDCs. It can complicate the cyst in approximately 1% of patients. Papillary carcinoma is the most common malignancy arising from a TDC. Follicular-papillary and Squamous cell carcinoma follow in order of commonality. (Option D) Cyst enlargement and compression of the underlying structures are other complications of TDCs. Obstruction of the airway is also significant. However, compared to infection and malignancy, this complication is less common. Rupture (option E) and fistula formation (option C) are other rare complications of a Thyroglossal duct cyst.`,
