    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `Children with Down syndrome have an increased risk of gastrointestinal tract anomalies, occurring in approximately 5%. These anomalies include duodenal atresia or stenosis (sometimes associated with annular pancreas—the most characteristic lesion, occurring in 2.5%), imperforate anus, esophageal atresia with tracheoesophageal fistula, and Hirschsprung disease (<1%). The early onset of bilious vomiting (6 hours after birth) is explicable by duodenal atresia as the most likely diagnosis. Option A: Although Hirschsprung disease can present in the neonatal period, especially in children with Down syndrome, typical presentation occurs 4 to 5 days after birth with constipation and progressive abdominal distention. Delayed passage of meconium is an early characteristic feature. Vomiting is not common. Option C: Necrotising enterocolitis is almost only seen in sick premature infants on maximum support during the acute stage of their complicated illness. Option D: In the neonatal period, malrotation with midgut volvulus may occur. Volvulus presents with abdominal pain that may be associated with bilious or non-bilious vomiting; however, Down syndrome, very early onset of vomiting, and vomiting immediately after breastfeeding is more consistent with duodenal atresia. Option E: Meconium plug syndrome tends to present later (2 to 3 days after birth) and is not associated with Down syndrome.`,
