    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Current Australian guidelines recommend antibiotic treatment of the index case with exclusion from childcare/school/work until non-infectious (after 5 days of antibiotics). Chemoprophylaxis of contacts is not routinely recommended due to delayed presentation and cost/adverse effects. However, given high risk of mortality in newborns and rising incidence, chemoprophylaxis is recommended for high-risk contacts. In this scenario, the parents do not meet criteria for prophylactic antibiotics as there is no other child <6 months in the house and they are not in close contact with other young children. However, they should receive booster immunization (dTpa or dTpa) as soon after exposure as possible, as they have not had pertussis-containing vaccine in the last 10 years. This protects them and reduces transmission risk.`,
