    correctAnswer: "E",
    explanation: `Seizure can be caused by metabolic derangements including hyponatremia, hypernatremia, hypocalcemia, and hypoglycemia. Key clues point to hyponatremia as the cause: the child is lethargic and confused with seizure. Hyponatremia presents with CNS manifestations including lethargy, headache, altered consciousness, and in severe cases, seizure, coma, or death. The child has normal urea and creatinine, ruling out acute renal failure. No signs of dehydration (normal mucous membranes, skin turgor, capillary refill), excluding hyponatremia due to dehydration. No history of congestive heart failure or clinical findings to support it. Addison disease presents with hyponatremia and hyperkalemia; this child has normal potassium and normal blood pressure. SIADH (syndrome of inappropriate anti-diuretic hormone) is caused by excess ADH from hypothalamus-pituitary unit, resulting in concentrated urine, increased body water, and hyponatremia through dilutional effect. Symptoms include nausea, vomiting, headache, confusion, seizures, and in severe cases coma. This best explains the presentation.`,
