    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `The Rinne and Weber tests quickly screen conductive versus sensorineural hearing loss. A positive Rinne test (AC > BC) for both ears excludes conductive impairment. The Weber test is normal (positive/typical) when the patient reports sound equally on both sides, indicating no lateralisation. Based on these findings, conductive causes (chronic perforation of tympanic membrane, chronic secretory otitis media, otosclerosis) are excluded. Presbycusis is the most common cause of sensorineural hearing loss in aging individuals and is unlikely in a 10-year-old. Given the exam findings and age, congenital sensorineural hearing loss, either in isolation or associated with a syndromic condition, is the most likely diagnosis. The symmetrical decreased hearing threshold affecting both ears equally supports a congenital sensorineural cause.`,
