    stem: `A 6-month-old male infant with Tetralogy of Fallot (TF) is brought to your clinic by his mother with history of nasal discharge, low-grade fever, feeding difficulty, wheezy breathing, and cough for 3 days. The infant's father smokes a pack of cigarettes per day at home. Physical examination is significant for inspiratory crackles and expiratory wheeze. Respiratory rate is 60 breaths per minute and oxygen saturation is 92% on room air. Which one of the following is the next best step in management?`,
