    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Proteinuria is defined as presence of 1+ protein or more on urine dipstick exam. To confirm the diagnosis of proteinuria, two consecutive urine dipsticks or urinalysis, 1 to 2 days apart must indicate proteinuria. If proteinuria persists on dipstick, the next best will be a complete urine exam (urinalysis) on a midstream urine sample obtained in the office for a more accurate assessment of the urine. With urinalysis (urine examination), the urine sediment, as well as other signs of glomerular and/or parenchymal disease such as hematuria, red cell casts, pyuria and/or lipiduria are assessed. Particular findings on urine examination may suggest glomerulonephritis, nephrotic syndrome, or other renal parenchymal disorders. Urinalysis may also suggest urinary tract infection with pyuria, bacteriuria, positive nitrites or leukocyte esterase, and mild proteinuria. Other initial laboratory evaluations include renal function tests (blood urea nitrogen and creatinine), serum electrolytes, cholesterol, albumin, and total protein. Another very important investigation to consider for this child is the urine protein/creatinine ratio on a first-morning void obtained at home as an estimation of the amount of protein excreted in 24 hours. Renal biopsy is not recommended routinely in children with asymptomatic persistent proteinuria. 12-hour urine protein is cumbersome and not necessary unless the patient is found to have an abnormal urine protein/creatinine ratio. Other tests such as renal ultrasound, serum complement levels (C3 and C4), antinuclear antibody (ANA), streptozyme testing, hepatitis B and C serology, and human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) testing should be considered based on the clinical setting. A voiding cystourethrogram should be considered if there is an abnormal ultrasound with scarring or a history of febrile urinary tract infections.`,
