    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Of the options, desmopressin (Minirin) spray is the most appropriate, and you should be advised to Ash's mother. This medication is used to treat primary nocturnal enuresis. It works by reducing the amount of urine production, hence decreasing the possibility of bedwetting. The recommended length of use is up to three months. Relapses are common after cessation of use, but in the short-term, it is often a convenient and effective treatment, making it a suitable option, especially at occasions such as camping and travelling when the child is not in the home setting. NOTE - for children, oral tablets or sublingual wafers are the recommended regimens, and intranasal use is discouraged due to the risk of hyponatremia. Fluid restriction is recommended from one hour before until eight hours after the desmopressin dose to maximise the medication's efficacy; however, fluid restriction as standalone therapy (option A) is not an effective treatment for preventing primary nocturnal enuresis. Not only does it not help, but it may also delay the achievement of dry nights. Waking up every two hours (option B) is inconvenient and disrupts Ash's sleep, so it should not be advised. A good night's sleep is important for children's health and well-being. Wearing nappies (option D) does not prevent the enuresis. Also, it could be embarrassing and inconvenient for Ash. Star charts (option E) and reward systems include rewarding the child either for a dry night or for correct toilet behaviour, regardless of the child actually being dry overnight. The rewards can range from stars on charts in the child's room or in the family room to pocket money or time earned for a preferred activity such as gaming. Star charts may be beneficial to some debatable extent for the treatment of enuresis. The reason it may not be as effective is that bedwetting is not a conscious before. Star charts take time to work on behavioural changes and, therefore, do not seem an appropriate option for the short-term management of Ash's bedwetting.`,
